<br>
Needing to vent? Get out paper, write it down and throw it out (don't leave it out she might read it).<br>
<br>
Yes, I told my mother I hated her, when I was 12.  I think he is a bit older than 12, regardless of how he acts.  What I did not do is go around telling my friends or strangers what a "bitch" she was.<br>
<br>
<br>
<b>Boycheese,</b><br>
<br>
I don't have a short temper when it comes to my mother.  I treat all my family and friends with respect (except my brother, who incidently I don't talk to because of the way he disrespects my parents).<br>
<br>
Your mama jokes are for children, and are normally said by people who don't really even know your mother.  They are a joke, obvious to everyone.  If you can not see the difference between that and calling your OWN mother a stupid bitch then you are slower than I have given you credit for.<br>
<br>
You say you have done plenty of respectful things for her.. how does that matter?  So a man who buys his wife lots of gifts and tells her he loves her has a right to verbally abuse her right?  What is the ratio of insults to compliments that makes it okay?<br>
<br>
If you say it will pass and you won't be mad then why do you feel the need to post this on the internet?  Just be glad your mom didn't see it.  When you tell someone "hey, you are a stupid fat pathetic slob who can't keep a job"... do you think it is okay if you say "just kidding"?<br>
<br>
I am very familiar with what sarcasm is, my friends would tell you I am too familiar with it, but what you said was not sarcasm, or was it?<br>
<br>
<b>sar·casm (särkzm)<br>
n. <br>
1.) A cutting, often ironic remark intended to wound. <br>
2.) A form of wit that is marked by the use of sarcastic language and is intended to make its victim the butt of contempt or ridicule.  </b><br>
<br>
Well, was it intended to wound her? Because it certainly wasn't a form of wit. <p>Cendan Tankenpriest<br>
